decimal;"><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>An MLB trifecta: Netflix, Fo=
x, and YouTube?</em>: With opening day just days away, MLB continues to plo=
t its next package of TV rights deals after its ESPN partnership expires in=
 October. At the moment, it seems clear that commissioner <strong>Rob Manfr=
ed</strong> is contemplating a patchwork approach, splitting game packages =
across a few different platforms. That makes sense, given baseball=E2=80=99=
s unusual status as a national pastime that=E2=80=99s mostly
enjoyed hyper-locally. Of course, Manfred probably dreams of transforming t=
he league into a streaming-first business, but that=E2=80=99s not where his=
 audience is right now. And although interest among younger fans is growing=
, the average baseball viewer=E2=80=99s age is still around 44, and roughly=
 12 to 32 percent of team revenues still come from local TV. It doesn=E2=80=
=99t help that sports viewers between 18 and 34 are <em>twice</em> as likel=
y to watch highlight clips on social media than to tune into a game=E2=80=
=A6 let
alone 162 of them.<br/><br/>In the short term, Manfred will likely have to =
forgo the traditional umbrella of rights packages, and pursue <em>=C3=A0 la=
 carte</em> positioning. Remember, the expiring ESPN package doesn=E2=80=99=
t include the World Series or playoff games. But Manfred <em>can</em> sell =
either smaller, habit-building events <em>or </em>popular one-offs: an excl=
usive weekly game, for example, or the Wild Card series, or the Home Run De=
rby, a player-focused one-off that could be a perfect fit for
Netflix=E2=80=99s sports strategy. Ted Sarandos hasn=E2=80=99t been coy abo=
ut wanting exactly this sort of big live-event programming, like the Christ=
mas NFL games that Netflix picked up this year.<br/><br/>Then there=E2=80=
=99s Fox, which needs more sports content for Tubi, the youngest-skewing of=
 all the major free, ad-supported streaming platforms in the U.S. So, it=E2=
=80=99s no surprise that <strong>Lachlan Murdoch </strong>has expressed int=
erest in expanding the network=E2=80=99s relationship with the league beyon=
d its current deal
to broadcast MLB games on Sundays. Fox has also expressed interest in pairi=
ng the Home Run Derby with the All-Star Game, putting both events on the sa=
me outlets to streamline ad sales and production.<br/><br/>YouTube should a=
lso be in the hunt. Alphabet=E2=80=99s video platform, driven by creators a=
nd personalities, would capitalize on the players=E2=80=99 personalities an=
d fans=E2=80=99 connections to individuals, not institutions. Indeed, non-M=
LB fans are already familiar with many players because of their popularity
on social platforms, like Instagram and YouTube Shorts. Allowing players to=
 simulcast game feeds would be one novel way to connect MLB with younger fa=
ns.</li><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>A Meta-UFC bromance</em>:<stro=
ng> Mark Zuckerberg</strong>=E2=80=99s decision to appoint <strong>Dana Whi=
te</strong> to Meta=E2=80=99s board of directors, in January, was widely pe=
rceived as a token of Zuck=E2=80=99s ongoing courtship of <strong>Donald</s=
trong> <strong>Trump</strong>. But it was also the culmination of a
three-year ringside friendship, stemming from Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s equally =
genuine, borderline obsessive enthusiasm for MMA. (He became an avid practi=
tioner of Brazilian jiujitsu during the pandemic; more recently, he accepte=
d <strong>Elon Musk</strong>=E2=80=99s challenge for a cage match that neve=
r happened.)<br/><br/>Anyway, Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s friendship with White is=
 probably worth keeping in mind ahead of the April 15 expiration of the neg=
otiating window for UFC=E2=80=99s current $450 million rights deal with ESP=
N, which
would end after this year. In 2023, Meta struck a deal with UFC to host the=
 league=E2=80=99s Fight Pass streaming service on its Quest platform. A dee=
per partnership could be lucrative for UFC, and give Meta the high-profile =
live events content it needs to boost sales of its virtual reality headsets=
 and drive engagement with its A.I. tools.<br/><br/>Everything comes down t=
o price. <strong>Ari Emanuel</strong>, the C.E.O. of UFC=E2=80=99s parent c=
ompany, TKO, is focused on boosting quarterly profits. It=E2=80=99s more
likely that he and White figure out a more exclusive deal with ESPN, or Net=
flix, or both. But Meta=E2=80=99s audience and technological prowess=E2=80=
=94a question mark for ESPN following all the streaming glitches that plagu=
ed the <strong>Alex Pereira</strong>=E2=80=93<strong>Magomed Ankalaev</stro=
ng> fight last weekend=E2=80=94could entice UFC if the league is looking fo=
r an additional partner.</li><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Netflix=
=E2=80=99s WWE bet</em>: While Netflix holds the title belt for
largest streamer=E2=80=94300 million global subs, billions of dollars in ne=
t profits=E2=80=94its foray into weekly live sports content with WWE <em>Ra=
w</em> is a painful reminder that even Netflix isn=E2=80=99t always finding=
 a Netflix-sized audience. According to Netflix data, global ratings for <e=
m>Raw </em>have averaged just north of 3 million households, a notable drop=
off from <em>Raw</em>=E2=80=99s Netflix premiere of 4.9 million. Analysts m=
ay want to see stronger numbers out of Netflix, but WWE execs should be
pleased with their audience growth. After all, it=E2=80=99s roughly double =
the average audience that <em>Raw </em>had on USA Network in 2024. Still, i=
t=E2=80=99s another data point indicating that a larger platform doesn=E2=
=80=99t automatically increase demand for a sport by an exorbitant multiple=
=2E Netflix=E2=80=99s two Christmas gam=
es=E2=80=94one with a halftime show by=
 <strong>Beyonc=C3=A9</strong>=E2=80=94averaged 26.5 million viewers.<br/><=
br/>Maybe it doesn=E2=80=99t matter: Sarandos suggested on the company=E2=
=80=99s last earnings call that current <em>Raw
</em>viewership is actually in line with internal modeling. Also, Netflix j=
ust announced that it sold out its title advertisements for the rest of <em=
>Raw</em>=E2=80=99s season. So it could be the case that while <em>Raw</em>=
 isn=E2=80=99t a blockbuster success, it=E2=80=99s also performing more or =
less as executives predicted. And it=E2=80=99s a good reminder that Netflix=
 has different goals than many of its linear competitors: It already has th=
e scale, now it needs eventized content that is attractive to advertisers.<=
/li>
